                      NPC Behavior General Description
                      ================================


Introduction:
------------

NPC behaviors are a generalized system for imparting intelligence and
flexibility to the actions of NPCs. These behaviors range from the 
benign, such as chatting, to specialized guild-based combat skill
techniques.


Concepts
--------

Each NPC now has a state, which describes the current situation of
the NPC. These states are defined in <npcstate.h>, and include:

NS_RESTING:  basic inactive state
NS_FIGHTING: currently engaged in combat
NS_HUNTING:  not fighting, but chasing down a previous attacker
NS_HEALING:  damaged, and not at maximum hit points

Each behavior can register itself as active during a particular
state or set of states. States are bitfields, and as such can be
ORed together. A behavior will only be queried for interest if
the NPC is currently in a state for which the behavior is
registered. Because a behavior can be registered for more than
one state, we can make behaviors that span more than just simple
situations.

There are also corresponding "anti-states", which are set to allow
behaviors based on the lack of a state:

NS_NOT_RESTING, NS_NOT_FIGHTING, NS_NOT_HUNTING, NS_NOT_HEALING

Behaviors are pluggable actions. They can be queried to decide if
they should be performed. They can also be given priorities, in order
to give the NPC a semblance of decision making capability.

Behaviors can be added and removed at any point in the lifetime of
the NPC. During each tick of the heartbeat, the list of behaviors
is first queried for "interest" using the query_interested function.
This function (in the inheritable) first checks to see if the state
of the NPC is one for which the behavior is registered. This function
can be overridden to add more complex decision functionality.

Once the list of interested behaviors has been created, the list
is sorted by query_priority. Priorities allow the behaviors to be
performed in order of most important. For example, an NPC that is
down to 10% of its hit points would place a very high priority on
casting a healing spell (if it has one), versus chasing its attackers
down.

The behaviors are executed in order of priority. Any commands that the
behaviors execute will subtract from the NPCs command points, and as
such the priority ensures that the most important actions are carried
out each heartbeat.


Basic Functionality
-------------------

Behaviors should inherit from the BEHAVIOR inheritable, as defined
in mudlib.h. This inheritable provides the basic functions necessary
for a pluggable behavior:

void set_state(int state);
int query_state();
- Sets and gets the states for which the behavior should be executed.

int query_interested(int state);
- Returns 1 if the behavior is interested in being performed this
  heartbeat, 0 if not. The parent BEHAVIOR will perform the state
  check, so doing so in children isn't necessary. Nor is it
  necessary to call ::query_interested(), as the actual test in
  BEHAVIOR is _query_interested. query_interested is just a hook
  that is called by _query_interested in the parent.

void set_priority(int priority)
- Behaviors define a basic integer priority which may be used if
  more complex behavior is not necessary.

int query_priority();
- Returns a priority from 0 to 100, with 100 being the highest. The
  priority is used to sort the behaviors before execution. NOTE: this
  function will NOT be called if there is only one interestd behavior
  in the queue!

int perform_behavior();
- Actually performs the actions associated with the behavior. Should
  return 1 if successful, 0 if not.

object query_local_npc()
- Returns the NPC for which this behavior is registered.

void set_local_npc(object npc) - SYSTEM FUNCTION
- Sets the NPC at behavior registration. Should not be used by wizards.

void activate()
- Turn the behavior on. A behavior can be registered but inactive, 
  allowing behaviors to turn themselves (and others!) on and off.
  activate() is called automatically when the behavior is registered
  by add_behavior().

void deactivate()
- Turn the behavior off.

int query_keep_awake()
- Return a 1 if the behavior wishes the NPC to stay awake even if
  there are no players in the same room. Used by the tracking
  behavior to continue tracking an aggressor, for example.

void set_keep_awake(int keep_awake)
- Set the keep awake of this behavior. 1 means the NPC won't go to sleep;
  0 means that it will.

void notify_awake()
- Notifies the behavior that the NPC is awake and receiving heart 
  beats. The NPC will go to sleep if there are no players in the
  same room, and if no behaviors return 1 from query_keep_awake().

void notify_asleep()
- Notifies the behavior that the NPC is asleep and not receiving
  heart beats. The NPC will go to sleep if there are no players in
  the same room, and if no behaviors return 1 from query_keep_awake().


NPCs define the following functions (from the NPCBEHAVE inheritable):

void set_behavior_state(int state)
- Sets the current NPC state.

int query_behavior_state()
- Returns the current NPC state.

void add_behavior(object behavior)
- Registers a new pluggable behavior for the NPC. Calls activate()
  on the behavior.

object *query_behaviors(string name)
- Returns all behaviors registered under the name. Behaviors can
  use the same name for grouping purposes; eg. several differnt
  "healing" behaviors utilizing different priorities and commands.

object query_behavior(string name)
- Returns the first behavior answering to the name. Typically this
  is sufficient, as there is usually only on behavior registerd
  for a particular name.

void reset_behaviors()
- Can be called by a behavior in the perform loop to cause the 
  entire query_interested/prioritization/perform process to start
  over. Useful if a behavior changes the NPC's state so drastically
  as to necessitate a recheck.

void remove_behavior(string name)
- Removes all behaviors registered under a particular name.

void behave()
- Loop through and perform all applicable behaviors.

Files
-----
/inherits/npcbehave.c
- Inherited into monster.c. Holds the code for the main behavior loop.

/inherits/behavior.c
- Inherited by all NPC behaviors. Has basic behavior functionality as
  described above.
           
/secure/include/npcstates.h
- #defines for the allowable NPC states.

/secure/include/behaviors.h
- Includes #defines for standard behaviors.

/objects/monsters/behaviors/*
- Standard NPC behaviors, such as chatting, wandering, and tracking.             


